SIMPLE: smith
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smith
<hw>Smith</hw> <pr>(sm⟦icr⟧th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>smi⟦edh⟧</ets>; akin to D. <ets>smid</ets>, G. <ets>schmied</ets>,
OHG. <ets>smid</ets>, Icel. <ets>smi⟦edh⟧r</ets>, Dan. & Sw.
<ets>smed</ets>, Goth. <ets>smi⟦thorn⟧a</ets> (in comp.); cf. Gr.
<grk>smi`lh</grk> a sort of knife, <grk>sminy`h</grk> a hoe,
mattock.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who forges with the hammer; one who
works in metals; <as>as, a black<ex>smith</ex>, gold<ex>smith</ex>,
silver<ex>smith</ex>, and the like</as>.</def> <rj><au>Piers
Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor yet the <qex>smith</qex> hath learned to form a sword.</q>
<rj><qau>Tate.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who makes or effects anything.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smith</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smith
<hw>Smith</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>smi⟦edh⟧ian</ets>. See
<er>Smith</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To beat into shape; to
forge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What smith that any [weapon] <qex>smitheth</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Piers Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smithcraft</ent>⟦br⟧
